A senior police officer was charged in Nairobi on Friday with renting guns to criminals. Senior Sergeant Gabriel Rotich, who is in charge of the armoury at DCI in Kiambu, appeared before Milimani senior resident magistrate Hellen Onkwani. He denied five counts of conspiracy to commit a felony, theft of three pistols and permitting falsification of register. The prosecution applied to cancel or enhance his cash bail of Sh400,000, saying he is flight risk and had been in hiding for nearly a week before surrendering. The prosecution told the court Rotich may abscond from court jurisdiction. But awyer G. Kanyi said his client is a police officer, a Kenyan citizen and will attend court as ordered. A ruling will on the prosecutionâ€™s application will be delivered on Tuesday next week. Gun recovered from thugs The charges state that on January 19 last year along Likoni road in Industrial Area in Nairobi, the accused conspired to commit a felony, with others not before the court. The prosecution also alleges that on December 17 and January 19 at Kiambu police station the suspect stole three firearms valued at Sh710,000 belonging to the state. Another count states the officer, having custody of the firearms register of Kiambu, entered false serial numbers. The suspected surrendered to police after hiding for close to a week. He presented himself to officers of the Special Crimes Prevention Unit at on Thursday afternoon in the company of his lawyer. The officer went missing last week hours after two suspected gangsters were shot dead in Industrial Area and a police gun was recovered from them. Evidence of collusion between police and criminal gangs emerged after guns from the Kiambu station were found in his house. Five pistols kept in a safe, intended to be exhibits in criminal prosecutions, appeared to have been handed to police officers on duty.